## Troubleshooting

### Backend won't start — migration error

```bash
# Check which migration failed
migrate -path backend/database/migrations \
        -database "postgres://..." version

# Force-reset a dirty migration (use with caution)
migrate -path backend/database/migrations \
        -database "postgres://..." force <version>
```

### 503 on all endpoints after start

The DB circuit breaker tripped. Check `/api/health/deep`:
```bash
curl http://localhost:8080/api/health/deep
```
The response shows which subsystem is down (Postgres, Redis, Kafka, Elasticsearch). The circuit resets automatically once the subsystem recovers.

### Agents show offline immediately

Check that the backend clock is NTP-synced. Agents are considered offline after 5 minutes without a heartbeat. Clock skew between agent hosts and the backend causes false offline status.

### WebSocket alerts not appearing in multi-replica setup

Verify Redis pub/sub is working:
```bash
redis-cli subscribe xcloak:ws:alerts
```
Trigger a test alert. If nothing arrives, check `REDIS_ADDR` is consistent across all replicas.

### Elasticsearch returning no results

Check the backend startup logs for `elasticsearch: connected`. The per-tenant index (`xcloak-logs-<tenant-id>`) is created on first ingest — if no logs have been ingested since Elasticsearch was enabled, the search will return empty (expected).

### Kafka consumer lag growing

```bash
kafka-consumer-groups.sh --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 --list | grep xcloak
kafka-consumer-groups.sh --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --describe --group xcloak-fim-consumer
```

All 7 consumer groups run in the same backend process. Each runs in an independent goroutine — a slow consumer does not block others. If the `fim` or `yara` consumer lags under heavy ingest, consider increasing topic partition counts for `xcloak.fim_alerts` and `xcloak.yara_matches`.

### JWT errors after key rotation

Rotating `JWT_SECRET` invalidates all existing sessions. All users must re-login. There is no zero-downtime key rotation in the current release — schedule a maintenance window.

### Mobile agent stuck "Offline"

1. Check that the backend is reachable from the device network (ping the server URL)
2. Check the agent foreground notification — if it says "Agent degraded" the device has hit 5 consecutive check-in failures
3. Verify the enrollment token was valid and the device is listed at **MDM → Devices**
4. On the device: Settings → Apps → XCloak Agent → Permissions → allow "Network" if restricted

---

## FAQ

**Q: Is the frontend (Next.js dashboard) open source?**  
A: The backend, Go agents, and mobile app are open source under BSL 1.1. The Next.js frontend is proprietary (open-core model). Contact abhishekn1003@gmail.com if you are interested in the frontend source.

**Q: Can I use XCloak in production?**  
A: Yes, but be aware it is a solo-maintained project with no commercial SLA. Review the [Security Audit Prep](https://github.com/The-Abhishek1/XCLOAK-SECURITY-SUITE/blob/main/docs/security-audit-prep.md) to understand the current security posture. A third-party pentest has not yet been conducted.

**Q: Does XCloak support iOS?**  
A: Not yet. The mobile agent is Android-only for now. iOS support is on the roadmap.

**Q: Does XCloak support macOS agents?**  
A: The Go agent compiles for macOS (`GOOS=darwin`), but macOS-specific collectors (Homebrew packages, macOS-native auth logs) are not yet implemented. macOS support is planned for v0.3.

**Q: What does "open-core" mean for licensing?**  
A: The backend and agents are licensed under BSL 1.1, which is source-available and converts to Apache 2.0 in 2029. You can self-host, modify, and contribute. Commercial use beyond the thresholds in the license file requires a separate agreement.

**Q: Can I run without Kafka?**  
A: Yes. Set `KAFKA_ENABLED=false` (the default). IOC matching and other async workloads will run synchronously. Kafka is recommended for high-volume environments (>10k events/s).

**Q: Can I run without Elasticsearch?**  
A: Yes. Omit `ELASTICSEARCH_URL`. Log search uses PostgreSQL full-text search as a fallback. Elasticsearch provides significantly better performance for large log volumes.

**Q: How do I reset the admin password?**  
A: Currently via the database directly:
```sql
UPDATE users SET password_hash = <new-bcrypt-hash> WHERE email = 'admin@example.com';
```
A UI-based admin password reset is planned for v0.3.

